'''Tezuka Mitsumori''' (手塚 光盛, ? - {{ill|Juei|ja|寿永|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 3rd year (1184)) was a {{ill|samurai|ja|武士|qq=draft|qq=draft}} during the late {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. He was a member of the {{ill|Kanemasa clan|ja|金刺氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who served as ritualists of the {{ill|Shimosha|ja|下社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of the {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. He was also known as Tezuka Betto's son (or nephew) and had an elder brother, {{ill|Kanemasa Morizumi|ja|金刺盛澄|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. His common name was Tarō.
In the {{ill|The Tale of the Heike|ja|平家物語|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Mitsumori is identified as a resident of {{ill|Shinano Province|ja|信濃国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, specifically in the {{ill|Suwa District|ja|諏訪郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Recent studies suggest that the Tezuka clan, including Mitsumori, was based in the {{ill|Tezuka area|ja|手塚 (上田市)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of {{ill|Ueda, Nagano|ja|上田市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} due to the presence of relics such as a residence site, {{ill|yabusame|ja|流鏑馬|qq=draft|qq=draft}} structures, a five-story stupa, and temples connected to Mitsumori’s legacy.<ref>Ueda City Historical Records (2001), "Manors and Samurai of Ueda," p. 27-31.</ref> However, no descendants of the Tezuka clan currently reside in the area. Tezuka-chō in {{ill|Kaga, Ishikawa|ja|石川県加賀市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} is named after Tezuka Tarō Mitsumori.
== Career == In {{ill|Jishō|ja|治承|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 4th year (1180), when Minamoto no Yoshinaka raised an army, Mitsumori joined as a prominent commander. In {{ill|Juei|ja|寿永|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 2nd year (1183), he participated in the {{ill|Battle of Shinohara|ja|篠原の戦い|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. An episode from this battle is notable in the {{ill|The Tale of the Heike|ja|平家物語|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, where Mitsumori defeated {{ill|Saitō Sanemori|ja|斎藤実盛|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
Sanemori, concealing his old age by dyeing his white hair black, fought valiantly in the colors of the general {{ill|Taira no Koremori|ja|平維盛|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. After a fierce duel, Mitsumori brought Sanemori's head back to Yoshinaka's camp. When the head was washed, the dye faded, revealing white hair. Recognizing the man as his savior during childhood, Yoshinaka wept openly.<ref>The Tale of the Heike.</ref>
In {{ill|Juei|ja|寿永|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 3rd year (1184), during the {{ill|Battle of Awazu|ja|粟津の戦い|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Mitsumori fought against the armies of {{ill|Minamoto no Noriyori|ja|源範頼|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshitsune|ja|源義経|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, dying alongside his lord Yoshinaka. He was one of the last loyal retainers to Yoshinaka.
== Descendants and Legacy == Tezuka Mitsumori is associated with several legends and remains: * His grave is located in {{ill|Tezuka area|ja|手塚 (上田市)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ueda, Nagano|ja|上田市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. * The Tezuka clan changed their surname to Tetsuka and established a memorial for Mitsumori in Osaka's {{ill|Tezukayama|ja|帝塚山|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
Mitsumori's lineage is said to include: * Tezuka Mitsuharu, a descendant who served as a {{ill|rangaku|ja|蘭学|qq=draft|qq=draft}} scholar. * {{ill|Osamu Tezuka|ja|手塚治虫|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a famous manga artist, is believed to be a 9th-generation descendant.<ref>Osamu Tezuka’s work "Phoenix" ("Civil War Chapter") references his lineage.</ref> == See Also == * {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Kanemasa clan|ja|金刺氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshinaka|ja|源義仲|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
