== Career ==
In {{ill|Jishō|en|Jishō|WD=Q1194671|lt=Jishō|1=Jishō}} 4th year (1180), when Minamoto no Yoshinaka raised an army, Mitsumori joined as a prominent commander. In {{ill|Juei|en|Juei|WD=Q598057|lt=Juei|1=Juei}} 2nd year (1183), he participated in the {{ill|Battle of Shinohara|en|Battle of Shinohara|WD=Q2889980|lt=Battle of Shinohara|1=Battle of Shinohara}}. An episode from this battle is notable in the {{ill|The Tale of the Heike|en|The Tale of the Heike|WD=Q830740|lt=The Tale of the Heike|1=The Tale of the Heike}}, where Mitsumori defeated {{ill|Saitō Sanemori|ja|斎藤実盛|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saitō Sanemori|1=Sanemori Saitō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q3472140}}.

Sanemori, concealing his old age by dyeing his white hair black, fought valiantly in the colors of the general {{ill|Taira no Koremori|en|Taira no Koremori|WD=Q3055506|lt=Taira no Koremori|1=Taira no Koremori}}. After a fierce duel, Mitsumori brought Sanemori's head back to Yoshinaka's camp. When the head was washed, the dye faded, revealing white hair. Recognizing the man as his savior during childhood, Yoshinaka wept openly.<ref>The Tale of the Heike.</ref>

In {{ill|Juei|en|Juei|WD=Q598057|lt=Juei|1=Juei}} 3rd year (1184), during the {{ill|Battle of Awazu|en|Battle of Awazu|WD=Q2237381|lt=Battle of Awazu|1=Battle of Awazu}}, Mitsumori fought against the armies of {{ill|Minamoto no Noriyori|en|Minamoto no Noriyori|WD=Q3142238|lt=Minamoto no Noriyori|1=Minamoto no Noriyori}} and {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshitsune|en|Minamoto no Yoshitsune|WD=Q310445|lt=Minamoto no Yoshitsune|1=Minamoto no Yoshitsune}}, dying alongside his lord Yoshinaka. He was one of the last loyal retainers to Yoshinaka.

== Descendants and Legacy ==
Tezuka Mitsumori is associated with several legends and remains:
* His grave is located in {{ill|Tezuka area|ja|手塚 (上田市)|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tezuka area|1=Q86729932|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q86729932}}, {{ill|Ueda, Nagano|en|Ueda, Nagano|WD=Q844852|lt=Ueda, Nagano|1=Ueda, Nagano}}.
* The Tezuka clan changed their surname to Tetsuka and established a memorial for Mitsumori in Osaka's {{ill|Tezukayama|ja|帝塚山|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tezukayama|1=Tezukayama|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11481044}}.

Mitsumori's lineage is said to include:
* Tezuka Mitsuharu, a descendant who served as a {{ill|Rangaku|en|Rangaku|WD=Q877637|lt=rangaku|1=Rangaku}} scholar.
